tar4ibd extends libtar with the following code:

+void
+long_to_oct_nonull(long num, char *oct, size_t octlen)
+{
+       char buf[100];

+       if (num >= 64 * 1024 * 1024 * 1024) {
+               fprintf(stderr, "Error: tar format cannot treat over 64GB file.\n");
+               exit(-1);
+       }
+
+       snprintf(buf, octlen + 1, "%0*lo", octlen, (unsigned long long)num);
+       strncpy(oct, buf, octlen);
+}

On 32-bit system long type is just 4 bytes, so it will not carry file sizes larger than 2GB properly (considering that it's signed). Also, the calculation 64*1024*1024*1024 may not be done properly until it's casted to a 64-bit type (i.e. long long).

