When running innobackupex from the command line, with a mysql user without password, the options passed to mysql are incorrect and cause the user specified on the command line to be ignored:

Reproduce
---------------

# Add backup user to mysql
mysql -u root -p
GRANT RELOAD, SUPER, REPLICATION CLIENT ON *.* TO 'backup'@'localhost';
GRANT CREATE, INSERT, DROP ON mysql.ibbackup_binlog_marker TO 'backup'@'localhost';
FLUSH PRIVILEGES;
QUIT;

# Run innobackup script (interactively as root to test all working)
/usr/bin/innobackupex --user=backup --defaults-file=/etc/mysql/my.cnf ./

Access denied for user root@localhost

Looking at the output, you see the following options being passed to the mysql child process : '--unbuffered -- --user=backup'
i.e. there's an extraneous '--'

Looking at the innobackup code, this is inserted if no password is specified, around line 996:

sub get_mysql_options {
    my $options = '--unbuffered';

    # prepare options for mysql
    if ($option_mysql_password) {
        $options = "$options --password=$option_mysql_password";
    }
    else {
        $options = "$options --";
    }
    if ($option_mysql_user) {
        $options = "$options --user=$option_mysql_user";
    }

Workaround
-----------------
I'm not sure what the else block trying to do if no password is specified, but commenting out/removing the password else block fixes this problem.

e.g.:

# prepare options for mysql
if ($option_mysql_password) {
    $options = "$options --password=$option_mysql_password";
}
#else {
#    $options = "$options --";
#}

Hope this helps others.

Cheers,
-Dan

